│ "old": "    // The original check only considered NaN issues, but we also   │
│ need to\n    // consider cases where the transformed operation could        │
│ produce poison\n    // due to restrictive fast-math flags on the binary     │
│ operator.\n    // However, after careful analysis, the correct fix is more  │
│ nuanced.\n    // The issue in the reproducer is specific to the case where  │
│ the true value\n    // is a binary operation with the same operand twice    │
│ (fmul x, x) and the\n    // condition checks if x == 0.\n    // In this     │
│ case, the original code only evaluates fmul x, x when x == 0,\n    // which │
│ is always safe (0*0=0).\n    // The transformed code always evaluates fmul  │
│ x, (select...), which can be\n    // poisonous if x violates the fast-math  │
│ flags.\n    // To fix this, we need to check if the false value could       │
│ violate the\n    // binary operator's fast-math flags.\n    if              │
│ (isa<FPMathOperator>(TVI)) {\n      // First, keep the original NaN check   │
│ using the select's fast-math flags\n      if                                │
│ (!computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, SelectFMF, fcNan, &SI).isKnownNeverNaN())\n │
│ return nullptr;\n      \n      // Now check if the false value could        │
│ violate the binary operator's\n      // ninf or nnan flags. We use empty    │
│ fast-math flags for the analysis\n      // to get the actual properties of  │
│ the value.\n      KnownFPClass KFPC = computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal,         │
│ FastMathFlags(), fcAllFlags, &SI);\n      if ((BinOpFMF.noInfs() &&         │
│ !KFPC.isKnownNeverInfinity()) ||\n          (BinOpFMF.noNaNs() &&           │
│ !KFPC.isKnownNeverNaN()))\n        return nullptr;\n    }", "new": "    //  │
│ The original check only considered NaN issues, but we also need to\n    //  │
│ consider cases where the transformed operation could produce poison\n    // │
│ due to restrictive fast-math flags on the binary operator.\n    // The      │
│ issue is most critical when the binary operation uses the same\n    //      │
│ operand twice (like fmul x, x) and the false value is that same operand.\n  │
│ // In such cases, the original code only evaluates the binary operation\n   │
│ // when the condition is true (e.g., x == 0), which is safe, but the\n      │
│ // transformed code always evaluates the binary operation, which can be\n   │
│ // poisonous if the operand violates the fast-math flags.\n    if           │
│ (isa<FPMathOperator>(TVI)) {\n      // First, keep the original NaN check   │
│ using the select's fast-math flags\n      if                                │
│ (!computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, SelectFMF, fcNan, &SI).isKnownNeverNaN())\n │
│ return nullptr;\n      \n      // Check if this is the problematic case:    │
│ binary op with identical operands\n      // and false value equals those    │
│ operands\n      Value *Op0 = TVI->getOperand(0);\n      Value *Op1 =        │
│ TVI->getOperand(1);\n      if (Op0 == Op1 && Op0 == FalseVal) {\n        // │
│ This is the reproducer case: (select cond, (binop x, x), x)\n        //     │
│ Check if the false value could violate the binary operator's flags\n        │
│ KnownFPClass KFPC = computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, FastMathFlags(),          │
│ fcAllFlags, &SI);\n        if ((BinOpFMF.noInfs() &&                        │
│ !KFPC.isKnownNeverInfinity()) ||\n            (BinOpFMF.noNaNs() &&         │
│ !KFPC.isKnownNeverNaN()))\n          return nullptr;\n      }\n    }"})     │
