│ "new": "    // The original check only considered NaN issues, but we also   │
│ need to\n    // consider cases where the transformed operation could        │
│ produce poison\n    // due to restrictive fast-math flags on the binary     │
│ operator.\n    // The specific bug occurs when we have (select cond, (binop │
│ x, x), x)\n    // with ninf/nnan flags, because the original code only      │
│ evaluates binop\n    // when cond is true (x == 0, which is safe), but the  │
│ transformed code\n    // always evaluates binop x, (select...), which can   │
│ be poisonous.\n    if (isa<FPMathOperator>(TVI)) {\n      // Keep the       │
│ original NaN check using the select's fast-math flags\n      if             │
│ (!computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, SelectFMF, fcNan, &SI).isKnownNeverNaN())\n │
│ return nullptr;\n      \n      // Check for the specific reproducer         │
│ pattern: (select cond, (binop x, x), x)\n      Value *Op0 =                 │
│ TVI->getOperand(0);\n      Value *Op1 = TVI->getOperand(1);\n      if (Op0  │
│ == Op1 && Op0 == FalseVal) {\n        // In this case, the original code    │
│ only evaluates binop when cond is true.\n        // For the reproducer,     │
│ cond is (x == 0), so when cond is true, x = 0,\n        // making binop(0,  │
│ 0) safe even with restrictive flags.\n        // But the transformed code   │
│ always evaluates binop(x, select...),\n        // which can be poisonous if │
│ x violates the flags.\n        KnownFPClass KFPC =                          │
│ computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, FastMathFlags(), fcAllFlags, &SI);\n          │
│ if ((BinOpFMF.noInfs() && !KFPC.isKnownNeverInfinity()) ||\n                │
│ (BinOpFMF.noNaNs() && !KFPC.isKnownNeverNaN()))\n          return           │
│ nullptr;\n      }\n    }"})                                                 │
